newsitem.title: USA: CME live cattle seen .10-.20 ct down, feeders weak.
newsitem.headline: CME live cattle seen .10-.20 ct down, feeders weak.

text.p: CME live cattle futures were called 0.10 to 0.20 cent per lb lower at the opening and feeder cattle steady to 0.10 cent lower, analysts said.
Analysts doubt there will be follow-through buying from the late gains in Wednesday's trading.
"There was nothing (fundamental) to substantiate it," said one analyst of the late gains.
Another analyst said "the cash news continues on the negative side. If we establish a cash (cattle) market it will be lower."
A few cattle traded Wednesday at $65.00 per cwt, down $1.00 from light $66.00 trades Tuesday and late last week.
Also, USDA reported beef cutout values continued to slide. Cutout values late Wednesday were down $1.01 to $0.42 per cwt, which followed declines Tuesday and Friday.
Feeder cattle were expected steady to 0.10 cent per lb lower at the opening on follow-through selling from Wednesday's lower close. Analysts said the long-term uptrend in feeder cattle may over.
The latest CME feeder cattle weighted average was $77.45 per cwt, down $0.15 from the previous one.
